# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: audio-synthesis
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] The timbre of musical instruments can be considered in the light of Fourier theory to consist of multiple harmonic or inharmonic *partials* or overtones.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Each partial is a sine wave of different frequency and amplitude that swells and decays over time due to modulation from an ADSR envelope or low-frequency oscillator.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Additive synthesis most directly generates sound by adding the output of multiple sine wave generators.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Alternative implementations may use pre-computed wavetables or the inverse fast Fourier transform.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] The sounds that are heard in everyday life are not characterized by a single frequency.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Instead, they consist of a sum of pure sine frequencies, each one at a different amplitude.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] When humans hear these frequencies simultaneously, we can recognize the sound.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] This is true for both "non-musical" sounds (e.g. water splashing, leaves rustling, etc.) and for "musical sounds" (e.g. a piano note, a bird's tweet, etc.).
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] This set of parameters (frequencies, their relative amplitudes, and how the relative amplitudes change over time) are encapsulated by the *timbre* of the sound.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Fourier analysis is the technique that is used to determine these exact timbre parameters from an overall sound signal; conversely, the resulting set of frequencies and amplitudes is called the Fourier series of the original sound signal.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] In the case of a musical note, the lowest frequency of its timbre is designated as the sound's fundamental frequency.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] For simplicity, we often say that the note is playing at that fundamental frequency (e.g.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] "middle C is 261.6 Hz"), even though the sound of that note consists of many other frequencies as well.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] The set of the remaining frequencies is called the overtones (or the harmonics, if their frequencies are integer multiples of the fundamental frequency) of the sound.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] In other words, the fundamental frequency alone is responsible for the pitch of the note, while the overtones define the timbre of the sound.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] The overtones of a piano playing middle C will be quite different from the overtones of a violin playing the same note; that's what allows us to differentiate the sounds of the two instruments.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] There are even subtle differences in timbre between different versions of the same instrument (for example, an upright piano vs. a grand piano).
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Additive synthesis aims to exploit this property of sound in order to construct timbre from the ground up.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] By adding together pure frequencies (sine waves) of varying frequencies and amplitudes, we can precisely define the timbre of the sound that we want to create.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Harmonic additive synthesis is closely related to the concept of a Fourier series which is a way of expressing a periodic function as the sum of sinusoidal functions with frequencies equal to integer multiples of a common fundamental frequency.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] These sinusoids are called harmonics, overtones, or generally, partials.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] In general, a Fourier series contains an infinite number of sinusoidal components, with no upper limit to the frequency of the sinusoidal functions and includes a DC component (one with frequency of 0 Hz).
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Frequencies outside of the human audible range can be omitted in additive synthesis.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] As a result, only a finite number of sinusoidal terms with frequencies that lie within the audible range are modeled in additive synthesis.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Being inaudible, the DC component, $a_{0}/2$ , and all components with frequencies higher than some finite limit, $Kf_{0}$ , are omitted in the following expressions of additive synthesis.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] where $y(t)$ is the synthesis output, $r_{k}$ , $kf_{0}$ , and $\phi _{k}$ are the amplitude, frequency, and the phase offset, respectively, of the k th harmonic partial of a total of K harmonic partials, and $f_{0}$ is the fundamental frequency of the waveform and the frequency of the musical note.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Each envelope $r_{k}(t)\,$ should vary slowly relative to the frequency spacing between adjacent sinusoids.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] The bandwidth of $r_{k}(t)$ should be significantly less than $f_{0}$ .
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Additive synthesis can also produce inharmonic sounds (which are aperiodic waveforms) in which the individual overtones need not have frequencies that are integer multiples of some common fundamental frequency.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] While many conventional musical instruments have harmonic partials (e.g. an oboe), some have inharmonic partials (e.g. bells).
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] where $f_{k}$ is the constant frequency of k th partial.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] In the general case, the instantaneous frequency of a sinusoid is the derivative (with respect to time) of the argument of the sine or cosine function.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] If this frequency is represented in hertz, rather than in angular frequency form, then this derivative is divided by $2\pi$ .
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] This is the case whether the partial is harmonic or inharmonic and whether its frequency is constant or time-varying.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Modern-day implementations of additive synthesis are mainly digital.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Additive synthesis can be implemented using a bank of sinusoidal oscillators, one for each partial.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] In the case of harmonic, quasi-periodic musical tones, wavetable synthesis can be as general as time-varying additive synthesis, but requires less computation during synthesis.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] As a result, an efficient implementation of time-varying additive synthesis of harmonic tones can be accomplished by use of *wavetable synthesis*.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Group additive synthesis is a method to group partials into harmonic groups (having different fundamental frequencies) and synthesize each group separately with *wavetable synthesis* before mixing the results.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] An inverse fast Fourier transform can be used to efficiently synthesize frequencies that evenly divide the transform period or "frame".
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] By careful consideration of the DFT frequency-domain representation it is also possible to efficiently synthesize sinusoids of arbitrary frequencies using a series of overlapping frames and the inverse fast Fourier transform.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] It is possible to analyze the frequency components of a recorded sound giving a "sum of sinusoids" representation.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] This representation can be re-synthesized using additive synthesis.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] One method of decomposing a sound into time varying sinusoidal partials is short-time Fourier transform (STFT)-based McAulay-Quatieri Analysis.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] By modifying the sum of sinusoids representation, timbral alterations can be made prior to resynthesis.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] For example, a harmonic sound could be restructured to sound inharmonic, and vice versa.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Sound hybridisation or "morphing" has been implemented by additive resynthesis.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Additive analysis/resynthesis has been employed in a number of techniques including Sinusoidal Modelling, Spectral Modelling Synthesis (SMS), and the Reassigned Bandwidth-Enhanced Additive Sound Model.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Software that implements additive analysis/resynthesis includes: SPEAR, LEMUR, LORIS, SMSTools, ARSS.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] New England Digital Synclavier had a resynthesis feature where samples could be analyzed and converted into "timbre frames" which were part of its additive synthesis engine.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Technos Acxel, launched in 1987, utilized the additive analysis/resynthesis model, in an FFT implementation.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Additive synthesis is used in electronic musical instruments.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] It is the principal sound generation technique used by Eminent organs.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] In linguistics research, harmonic additive synthesis was used in the 1950s to play back modified and synthetic speech spectrograms.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Later, in the early 1980s, listening tests were carried out on synthetic speech stripped of acoustic cues to assess their significance.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Time-varying formant frequencies and amplitudes derived by linear predictive coding were synthesized additively as pure tone whistles.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] This method is called sinewave synthesis.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Also the composite sinusoidal modeling (CSM) used on a singing speech synthesis feature on the Yamaha CX5M (1984), is known to use a similar approach which was independently developed during 1966–1979.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] These methods are characterized by extraction and recomposition of a set of significant spectral peaks corresponding to the several resonance modes occurring in the oral cavity and nasal cavity, in a viewpoint of acoustics.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] This principle was also utilized on a physical modeling synthesis method, called modal synthesis.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Harmonic analysis was discovered by Joseph Fourier, who published an extensive treatise of his research in the context of heat transfer in 1822.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] The theory found an early application in prediction of tides.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Around 1876, William Thomson (later ennobled as Lord Kelvin) constructed a mechanical tide predictor.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] It consisted of a *harmonic analyzer* and a *harmonic synthesizer*, as they were called already in the 19th century.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] The analysis of tide measurements was done using James Thomson's *integrating machine*.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] The resulting Fourier coefficients were input into the synthesizer, which then used a system of cords and pulleys to generate and sum harmonic sinusoidal partials for prediction of future tides.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] In 1910, a similar machine was built for the analysis of periodic waveforms of sound.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] The synthesizer drew a graph of the combination waveform, which was used chiefly for visual validation of the analysis.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Georg Ohm applied Fourier's theory to sound in 1843.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] The line of work was greatly advanced by Hermann von Helmholtz, who published his eight years worth of research in 1863.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Helmholtz believed that the psychological perception of tone color is subject to learning, while hearing in the sensory sense is purely physiological.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] He supported the idea that perception of sound derives from signals from nerve cells of the basilar membrane and that the elastic appendages of these cells are sympathetically vibrated by pure sinusoidal tones of appropriate frequencies.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Helmholtz agreed with the finding of Ernst Chladni from 1787 that certain sound sources have inharmonic vibration modes.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] In Helmholtz's time, electronic amplification was unavailable.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] For synthesis of tones with harmonic partials, Helmholtz built an electrically excited array of tuning forks and acoustic resonance chambers that allowed adjustment of the amplitudes of the partials.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Built at least as early as in 1862, these were in turn refined by Rudolph Koenig, who demonstrated his own setup in 1872.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] For harmonic synthesis, Koenig also built a large apparatus based on his *wave siren*.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] It was pneumatic and utilized cut-out tonewheels, and was criticized for low purity of its partial tones.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Also tibia pipes of pipe organs have nearly sinusoidal waveforms and can be combined in the manner of additive synthesis.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] In 1938, with significant new supporting evidence, it was reported on the pages of Popular Science Monthly that the human vocal cords function like a fire siren to produce a harmonic-rich tone, which is then filtered by the vocal tract to produce different vowel tones.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] By the time, the additive Hammond organ was already on market.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Most early electronic organ makers thought it too expensive to manufacture the plurality of oscillators required by additive organs, and began instead to build subtractive ones.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] In a 1940 Institute of Radio Engineers meeting, the head field engineer of Hammond elaborated on the company's new *Novachord* as having a *"subtractive system"* in contrast to the original Hammond organ in which *"the final tones were built up by combining sound waves"*.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] Alan Douglas used the qualifiers *additive* and *subtractive* to describe different types of electronic organs in a 1948 paper presented to the Royal Musical Association.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] A typical modern additive synthesizer produces its output as an electrical, analog signal, or as digital audio, such as in the case of software synthesizers, which became popular around year 2000.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] The following is a timeline of historically and technologically notable analog and digital synthesizers and devices implementing additive synthesis.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] In digital implementations of additive synthesis, discrete-time equations are used in place of the continuous-time synthesis equations.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] A notational convention for discrete-time signals uses brackets i.e. $y[n]\,$ and the argument $n\,$ can only be integer values.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] If the continuous-time synthesis output $y(t)\,$ is expected to be sufficiently bandlimited; below half the sampling rate or $f_{\mathrm {s} }/2\,$ , it suffices to directly sample the continuous-time expression to get the discrete synthesis equation.
[src:audio-synthesis/additive-synthesis] The continuous synthesis output can later be reconstructed from the samples using a digital-to-analog converter.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] Developed in the 1960s by researchers at Stanford University, then commercialized through digital instruments such as the Yamaha GS-1 and popularized by the Yamaha DX7 in the 1980s, FM synthesis has had a lasting influence on recorded music, electronic music, popular music, and video game music.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] It became closely associated with the sound of the 1980s, while related Yamaha FM chips gave many arcade games, home computers, game consoles, sound cards, and early mobile phone ringtones their characteristic timbres.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] Its spread from Stanford University computer-music research into studios, homes, arcades, and consumer devices has made FM synthesis one of the most widely heard forms of digital synthesis of the late-20th century.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] FM synthesis can create both harmonic and inharmonic sounds.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] To synthesize harmonic sounds, the modulating signal must have a harmonic relationship to the original carrier signal.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] As the amount of frequency modulation increases, the sound grows progressively complex.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] Through the use of modulators with frequencies that are non-integer multiples of the carrier signal (i.e. inharmonic), inharmonic bell-like and percussive spectra can be created.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] FM synthesis using analog oscillators may result in pitch instability.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] However, FM synthesis can also be implemented digitally, which is more stable and became standard practice.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] Digital FM synthesis (equivalent to phase modulation using the time integration of instantaneous frequency) was the basis of several musical instruments beginning as early as 1974.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] Yamaha built the first prototype digital synthesizer in 1974, based on FM synthesis, before commercially releasing the Yamaha GS-1 in 1980.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] The Synclavier I, manufactured by New England Digital Corporation beginning in 1978, had an optional digital FM synthesis module (later built into the Synclavier II) which could be added on to the synthesizer, using an FM synthesis algorithm licensed from Yamaha.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] Yamaha's groundbreaking Yamaha DX7 synthesizer, released in 1983, brought FM to the forefront of synthesis in the mid-1980s.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] FM synthesis also became the usual setting for games and software up until the mid-nineties.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] Sound cards for IBM PC compatible systems like the AdLib and Sound Blaster popularized Yamaha chips like the OPL2 and OPL3.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] Other computers such as the Sharp X68000 and MSX (Yamaha CX5M computer unit) utilize the OPM sound chip (with later CX5M units using the similar OPP sound chip).
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] The NEC PC-88 and PC-98 computers use either the OPN and OPNA sound chips.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] For arcade systems and game consoles, the OPM was widely used in many arcade boards from the 1980s and 1990s (including Sega's System 16 and Capcom's CP System arcade boards); the similar OPN was also used in some arcade boards in the 1980s.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] OPNB was notably used in SNK's Neo Geo arcade (MVS) and home console (AES) machines, as well as being used as the main basic sound generator in Taito's arcade boards (with a variant of the OPNB being used in several arcade boards such as the Taito Z System board).
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] The related OPN2 was used in Sega's Mega Drive (Genesis), Fujitsu's FM Towns Marty, and some of Sega's arcade boards (e.g.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] Sega System C-2 and Sega System 32) as one of its sound generator chips.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] FM synthesis was also used on a wide range of mobile phones in the 2000s to play ringtones and other sounds, using the Yamaha SMAF format.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] Don Buchla implemented FM on his instruments in the mid-1960s, prior to Chowning's patent.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] His 158, 258 and 259 dual oscillator modules had a specific FM control voltage input, and the model 208 (Music Easel) had a modulation oscillator hard-wired to allow FM as well as AM of the primary oscillator.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] These early applications used analog oscillators, and this capability was also followed by other modular synthesizers and portable synthesizers including Minimoog and ARP Odyssey.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] By the mid-20th century, frequency modulation (FM), a means of carrying sound, had been understood for decades and was being used to broadcast radio transmissions.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] FM synthesis was developed since 1967 at Stanford University, California, by John Chowning, through his exploration of digital synthesis and spatialization, inspired by the new possibilities of digital sound as described by Max Mathews.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] His algorithm was licensed to Japanese company Yamaha in 1973.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] The implementation commercialized by Yamaha (US Patent 4018121 Apr 1977 or U.S.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] Patent 4,018,121) is actually based on phase modulation, but the results end up being equivalent mathematically as both are essentially a special case of quadrature amplitude modulation.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] In the 1970s, Yamaha were granted a number of patents, under the company's former name "Nippon Gakki Seizo Kabushiki Kaisha", evolving Chowning's work.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] Yamaha built the first prototype FM digital synthesizer in 1974.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] Yamaha eventually commercialized FM synthesis technology with the Yamaha GS-1, the first FM digital synthesizer, released in 1980.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] FM synthesis was the basis of some of the early generations of digital synthesizers, most notably those from Yamaha, as well as New England Digital Corporation under license from Yamaha.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] Yamaha's DX7 synthesizer, released in 1983, was ubiquitous throughout the 1980s.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] Yamaha had patented its hardware implementation of FM in the 1970s, allowing it to nearly monopolize the market for FM technology until the mid-1990s.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] Casio developed a related form of synthesis called phase distortion synthesis, used in its CZ range of synthesizers.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] It had a similar (but slightly differently derived) sound quality to the DX series.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] With the expiration of the Stanford University FM patent in 1995, digital FM synthesis can now be implemented freely by other manufacturers.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] The FM synthesis patent brought Stanford $20 million before it expired, making it (in 1994) "the second most lucrative licensing agreement in Stanford's history".
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] The degree of complexity of the FM in such hardware synths may vary from simple 2-operator FM, to the highly flexible 6-operator engines of the Korg Kronos and Alesis Fusion, to creation of FM in extensively modular engines such as those in the latest synthesisers by Kurzweil Music Systems.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] The Yamaha SY77, Yamaha SY99 and FS1R synthesizers marketed their highly powerful FM abilities as counterparts to sample-based synthesis and formant synthesis respectively.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] Various other synthesizers offer limited FM abilities to supplement their main engines.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] The FS1R had 16 operators, 8 standard FM operators and 8 additional operators that used a noise source rather than an oscillator as its sound source.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] By adding in tuneable noise sources the FS1R could model the sounds produced in the human voice and in a wind instrument, along with making percussion instrument sounds.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] The FS1R also contained an additional wave form called the Formant wave form.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] Formants can be used to model resonating body instrument sounds like the cello, violin, acoustic guitar, bassoon, English horn, or human voice.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] Formants can even be found in the harmonic spectrum of several brass instruments.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] In 2016, Korg released the Korg Volca FM, a, 3-voice, 6 operators FM iteration of the Korg Volca series of compact, affordable desktop modules.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] Korg has also released the opsix (2020) and opsix SE (2023), integrating 6 operators FM synthesis with subtractive, analogue modeling, additive, semi-modular and Waveshaping.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] Yamaha released the Montage in 2016, which combines a 128-voice sample-based engine with a 128-voice FM engine.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] This iteration of FM is called FM-X, and features 8 operators; each operator has a choice of several basic wave forms, but each wave form has several parameters to adjust its spectrum.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] It was then followed by the more affordable Yamaha MODX in 2018, with 64-voice, 8 operators FM-X architecture in addition to a 128-voice sample-based engine.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] The MODX+ released in 2022 increased the number of voices of the FM-X engine to 128, the same as with the Montage.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] The Montage was succeeded by the Montage M in 2023, which uses the same 128-voice, 8 operators FM-X engine alongside a 128-voice sample-based engine and a newly introduced 16-voice 3 oscillator analog-based engine known as AN-X.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] Elektron launched the Digitone in 2018, which is an 8-voice, 4 operators FM synth featuring Elektron's renowned sequence engine.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] FM-X synthesis was first introduced with the Yamaha Montage synthesizers in 2016.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] Each FM-X operator has a set of multi-spectral wave forms to choose from, which means each FM-X operator can be equivalent to a stack of 3 or 4 DX7 FM operators.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] The list of selectable wave forms includes sine waves, the All1 and All2 wave forms, the Odd1 and Odd2 wave forms, and the Res1 and Res2 wave forms.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] The sine wave selection works the same as the DX7 wave forms.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] The All1 and All2 wave forms are a saw-tooth wave form.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] The Odd1 and Odd2 wave forms are pulse or square waves.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] These two types of wave forms can be used to model the basic harmonic peaks in the bottom of the harmonic spectrum of most instruments.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] The Res1 and Res2 wave forms move the spectral peak to a specific harmonic and can be used to model either triangular or rounded groups of harmonics further up in the spectrum of an instrument.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] Combining an All1 or Odd1 wave form with multiple Res1 (or Res2) wave forms (and adjusting their amplitudes) can model the harmonic spectrum of an instrument or sound.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] Combining sets of 8 FM operators with multi-spectral wave forms was first introduced in the FS1R, released in 1999 by Yamaha.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] It was able to achieve similar results to that of FM-X using 8 noise operators.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] As the basic of these variations, we analyze the spectrum of 2 operators (linear FM synthesis using two sinusoidal operators) on the following.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] If we were to ignore the constant phase terms on the carrier $\phi _{c}=B/\omega _{m}\,$ and the modulator $\phi _{m}=-\pi /2\,$ , finally we would get the following expression, as seen on Chowning 1973 and Roads 1996, p.
[src:audio-synthesis/frequency-modulation-synthesis] where $\omega _{c}\,,\,\omega _{m}\,$ are angular frequencies ( $\,\omega =2\pi f\,$ ) of carrier and modulator, $\beta =B/\omega _{m}\,$ is frequency modulation index, and amplitudes $J_{n}(\beta )\,$ is $n\,$ -th Bessel function of first kind, respectively.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] An **electronic oscillator** is an electronic circuit that produces a periodic, oscillating or alternating current (AC) signal, usually a sine wave, square wave or a triangle wave, powered by a direct current (DC) source.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] Oscillators are found in many electronic devices, such as radio receivers, television sets, radio and television broadcast transmitters, computers, computer peripherals, cellphones, radar, and many other devices.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] There are two general types of electronic oscillators: the **linear** or **harmonic oscillator**, and the **nonlinear** or **relaxation oscillator**.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] The two types are fundamentally different in how oscillation is produced, as well as in the characteristic type of output signal that is generated.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] The most-common linear oscillator in use is the crystal oscillator, in which the output frequency is controlled by a piezo-electric resonator consisting of a vibrating quartz crystal.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] Crystal oscillators are ubiquitous in modern electronics, being the source for the clock signal in computers and digital watches, as well as a source for the signals generated in radio transmitters and receivers.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] As a crystal oscillator's “native” output waveform is sinusoidal, a signal-conditioning circuit may be used to convert the output to other waveform types, such as the square wave typically utilized in computer clock circuits.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] The most common form of linear oscillator is an electronic amplifier such as a transistor or operational amplifier connected in a feedback loop with its output fed back into its input through a frequency selective electronic filter to provide positive feedback.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] When the power supply to the amplifier is switched on initially, electronic noise in the circuit provides a non-zero signal to get oscillations started.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] The noise travels around the loop and is amplified and filtered until very quickly it converges on a sine wave at a single frequency.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] Typical block diagram of a negative resistance oscillator.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] In some types the negative resistance device is connected in parallel with the resonant circuit.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] Negative-resistance oscillators are usually used at high frequencies in the microwave range and above, since at these frequencies feedback oscillators perform poorly due to excessive phase shift in the feedback path.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] In negative-resistance oscillators, a resonant circuit, such as an LC circuit, crystal, or cavity resonator, is connected across a device with negative differential resistance, and a DC bias voltage is applied to supply energy.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] A resonant circuit by itself is "almost" an oscillator; it can store energy in the form of electronic oscillations if excited, but because it has electrical resistance and other losses the oscillations are damped and decay to zero.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] The negative resistance of the active device cancels the (positive) internal loss resistance in the resonator, in effect creating a resonator circuit with no damping, which generates spontaneous continuous oscillations at its resonant frequency.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] The negative-resistance oscillator model is not limited to one-port devices like diodes; feedback oscillator circuits with two-port amplifying devices such as transistors and tubes also have negative resistance.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] At high frequencies, three terminal devices such as transistors and FETs are also used in negative resistance oscillators.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] At high frequencies these devices do not need a feedback loop, but with certain loads applied to one port can become unstable at the other port and show negative resistance due to internal feedback.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] The negative resistance port is connected to a tuned circuit or resonant cavity, causing them to oscillate.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] High-frequency oscillators in general are designed using negative-resistance techniques.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] A **nonlinear** or **relaxation oscillator** produces a non-sinusoidal output, such as a square, sawtooth or triangle wave.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] It consists of an energy-storing element (a capacitor or, more rarely, an inductor) and a nonlinear switching device (a latch, Schmitt trigger, or negative resistance element) connected in a feedback loop.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] The switching device periodically charges the storage element with energy and when its voltage or current reaches a threshold discharges it again, thus causing abrupt changes in the output waveform.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] Although in the past negative resistance devices like the unijunction transistor, thyratron tube or neon lamp were used, today relaxation oscillators are mainly built with integrated circuits like the 555 timer IC.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] Square-wave relaxation oscillators are used to provide the clock signal for sequential logic circuits such as timers and counters, although crystal oscillators are often preferred for their greater stability.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] Triangle-wave or sawtooth oscillators are used in the timebase circuits that generate the horizontal deflection signals for cathode-ray tubes in analogue oscilloscopes and television sets.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] They are also used in voltage-controlled oscillators (VCOs), inverters and switching power supplies, dual-slope analog to digital converters (ADCs), and in function generators to generate square and triangle waves for testing equipment.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] In general, relaxation oscillators are used at lower frequencies and have poorer frequency stability than linear oscillators.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] Ring oscillators are built of a ring of active delay stages, such as inverters.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] Generally the ring has an odd number of inverting stages, so that there is no single stable state for the internal ring voltages.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] Instead, a single transition propagates endlessly around the ring.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] An oscillator can be designed so that the oscillation frequency can be varied over some range by an input voltage or current.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] These voltage-controlled oscillators are widely used in phase-locked loops, in which the oscillator's frequency can be locked to the frequency of another oscillator.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] These are ubiquitous in modern communications circuits, used in filters, modulators, demodulators, and forming the basis of frequency synthesizer circuits which are used to tune radios and televisions.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] Radio frequency VCOs are usually made by adding a varactor diode to the tuned circuit or resonator in an oscillator circuit.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] Changing the DC voltage across the varactor changes its capacitance, which changes the resonant frequency of the tuned circuit.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] Voltage-controlled relaxation oscillators can be constructed by charging and discharging the energy storage capacitor with a voltage-controlled current source.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] Increasing the input voltage increases the rate of charging the capacitor, decreasing the time between switching events.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] A feedback oscillator circuit consists of two parts connected in a feedback loop; an amplifier A and an electronic filter $\beta (j\omega )$ .
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] The filter's purpose is to limit the frequencies that can pass through the loop so the circuit only oscillates at the desired frequency.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] Since the filter and wires in the circuit have resistance they consume energy and the amplitude of the signal drops as it passes through the filter.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] The amplifier is needed to increase the amplitude of the signal to compensate for the energy lost in the other parts of the circuit, so the loop will oscillate, as well as supply energy to the load attached to the output.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] The ratio of output to input of the loop, ${v_{o} \over v_{i}}=A\beta (j\omega )$ , is called the loop gain.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] If the loop gain were less than one, the signal would decrease around the loop, resulting in an exponentially decaying sine wave that decreases to zero.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] Equations (1) and (2) are called the *Barkhausen stability criterion*.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] It is a necessary but not a sufficient criterion for oscillation, so there are some circuits which satisfy these equations that will not oscillate.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] An equivalent condition often used instead of the Barkhausen condition is that the circuit's closed loop transfer function (the circuit's complex impedance at its output) have a pair of poles on the imaginary axis.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] In general, the phase shift of the feedback network increases with increasing frequency so there are only a few discrete frequencies (often only one) which satisfy the second equation.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] If the amplifier gain A is high enough that the loop gain is unity (or greater, see Startup section) at one of these frequencies, the circuit will oscillate at that frequency.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] Many amplifiers such as common-emitter transistor circuits are "inverting", meaning that their output voltage decreases when their input increases.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] In these the amplifier provides 180° phase shift, so the circuit will oscillate at the frequency at which the feedback network provides the other 180° phase shift.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] An alternate mathematical stability test sometimes used instead of the Barkhausen criterion is the Nyquist stability criterion.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] This has a wider applicability than the Barkhausen, so it can identify some of the circuits which pass the Barkhausen criterion but do not oscillate.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] Temperature changes, other environmental changes, aging, and manufacturing tolerances will cause component values to "drift" away from their designed values.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] Changes in *frequency determining* components such as the tank circuit in LC oscillators will cause the oscillation frequency to change, so for a constant frequency these components must have stable values.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] How stable the oscillator's frequency is to other changes in the circuit, such as changes in values of other components, gain of the amplifier, the load impedance, or the supply voltage, is mainly dependent on the Q factor ("quality factor") of the feedback filter.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] Since the *amplitude* of the output is constant due to the nonlinearity of the amplifier (see Startup section below), changes in component values cause changes in the phase shift $\phi \;=\;\angle A\beta (j\omega )$ of the feedback loop.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] Since oscillation can only occur at frequencies where the phase shift is a multiple of 360°, $\phi \;=\;360n^{\circ }$ , shifts in component values cause the oscillation frequency $\omega _{0}$ to change to bring the loop phase back to 360n°.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] RC oscillators have the equivalent of a very low Q , so the phase changes very slowly with frequency, therefore a given phase change will cause a large change in the frequency.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] In contrast, LC oscillators have tank circuits with high Q (~102).
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] This means the phase shift of the feedback network increases rapidly with frequency near the resonant frequency of the tank circuit.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] So a large change in phase causes only a small change in frequency.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] Therefore, the circuit's oscillation frequency is very close to the natural resonant frequency of the tuned circuit, and doesn't depend much on other components in the circuit.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] The quartz crystal resonators used in crystal oscillators have even higher Q (104 to 106) and their frequency is very stable and independent of other circuit components.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] The frequency of RC and LC oscillators can be tuned over a wide range by using variable components in the filter.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] A microwave cavity can be tuned mechanically by moving one of the walls.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] In contrast, a quartz crystal is a mechanical resonator whose resonant frequency is mainly determined by its dimensions, so a crystal oscillator's frequency is only adjustable over a very narrow range, a tiny fraction of one percent.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] Its frequency can be changed slightly by using a trimmer capacitor in series or parallel with the crystal.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] (1) and (2), merely gives the frequencies at which steady-state oscillation is possible, but says nothing about the amplitude of the oscillation, whether the amplitude is stable, or whether the circuit will start oscillating when the power is turned on.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] A typical rule of thumb is to make the small signal loop gain at the oscillation frequency 2 or 3.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] When the power is turned on, oscillation is started by the power turn-on transient or random electronic noise present in the circuit.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] Noise guarantees that the circuit will not remain "balanced" precisely at its unstable DC equilibrium point (Q point) indefinitely.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] Due to the narrow passband of the filter, the response of the circuit to a noise pulse will be sinusoidal, it will excite a small sine wave of voltage in the loop.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] Since for small signals the loop gain is greater than one, the amplitude of the sine wave increases exponentially.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] During startup, while the amplitude of the oscillation is small, the circuit is approximately linear, so the analysis used in the Barkhausen criterion is applicable.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] When the amplitude becomes large enough that the amplifier becomes nonlinear, generating harmonic distortion, technically the frequency domain analysis used in normal amplifier circuits is no longer applicable, so the "gain" of the circuit is undefined.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] However the filter attenuates the harmonic components produced by the nonlinearity of the amplifier, so the fundamental frequency component $\sin \omega _{0}t$ mainly determines the loop gain (this is the "harmonic balance" analysis technique for nonlinear circuits).
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] The sine wave cannot grow indefinitely; in all real oscillators some nonlinear process in the circuit limits its amplitude, reducing the gain as the amplitude increases, resulting in stable operation at some constant amplitude.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] In most oscillators this nonlinearity is simply the saturation (limiting or clipping) of the amplifying device, the transistor, vacuum tube or op-amp.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] The maximum voltage swing of the amplifier's output is limited by the DC voltage provided by its power supply.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] Another possibility is that the output may be limited by the amplifier slew rate.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] As the amplitude of the output nears the power supply voltage rails, the amplifier begins to saturate on the peaks (top and bottom) of the sine wave, flattening or "clipping" the peaks.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] To achieve the maximum amplitude sine wave output from the circuit, the amplifier should be biased midway between its clipping levels.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] For example, an op amp should be biased midway between the two supply voltage rails.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] A common-emitter transistor amplifier's collector voltage should be biased midway between cutoff and saturation levels.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] Since the output of the amplifier can no longer increase with increasing input, further increases in amplitude cause the equivalent gain of the amplifier and thus the loop gain to decrease.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] This is a stable equilibrium; if the amplitude of the sine wave increases for some reason, increased clipping of the output causes the loop gain $|A\beta (j\omega _{0})|$ to drop below one temporarily, reducing the sine wave's amplitude back to its unity-gain value.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] Similarly if the amplitude of the wave decreases, the decreased clipping will cause the loop gain to increase above one, increasing the amplitude.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] An exception to the above are high Q oscillator circuits such as crystal oscillators; the narrow bandwidth of the crystal removes the harmonics from the output, producing a 'pure' sinusoidal wave with almost no distortion even with large loop gains.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] Since oscillators depend on nonlinearity for their operation, the usual linear frequency domain circuit analysis techniques used for amplifiers based on the Laplace transform, such as root locus and gain and phase plots (Bode plots), cannot capture their full behavior.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] To determine startup and transient behavior and calculate the detailed shape of the output waveform, electronic circuit simulation computer programs like SPICE are used.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] Component values are tweaked until the simulation results are satisfactory.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] The distorted oscillations of real-world (nonlinear) oscillators are called limit cycles and are studied in nonlinear control theory.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] In applications where a 'pure' very low distortion sine wave is needed, such as precision signal generators, a nonlinear component is often used in the feedback loop that provides a 'slow' gain reduction with amplitude.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] This stabilizes the loop gain at an amplitude below the saturation level of the amplifier, so it does not saturate and "clip" the sine wave.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] Resistor-diode networks and FETs are often used for the nonlinear element.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] An older design uses a thermistor or an ordinary incandescent light bulb; both provide a resistance that increases with temperature as the current through them increases.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] As the amplitude of the signal current through them increases during oscillator startup, the increasing resistance of these devices reduces the loop gain.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] The essential characteristic of all these circuits is that the nonlinear gain-control circuit must have a long time constant, much longer than a single period of the oscillation.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] Therefore, over a single cycle they act as virtually linear elements, and so introduce very little distortion.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] The operation of these circuits is somewhat analogous to an automatic gain control (AGC) circuit in a radio receiver.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] The Wien bridge oscillator is a widely used circuit in which this type of gain stabilization is used.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] At high frequencies it becomes difficult to physically implement feedback oscillators because of shortcomings of the components.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] Since at high frequencies the tank circuit has very small capacitance and inductance, parasitic capacitance and parasitic inductance of component leads and PCB traces become significant.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] These may create unwanted feedback paths between the output and input of the active device, creating instability and oscillations at unwanted frequencies (parasitic oscillation).
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] Parasitic feedback paths inside the active device itself, such as the interelectrode capacitance between output and input, make the device unstable.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] The input impedance of the active device falls with frequency, so it may load the feedback network.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] As a result, stable feedback oscillators are difficult to build for frequencies above 500 MHz, and negative resistance oscillators are usually used for frequencies above this.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] The first practical oscillators were based on electric arcs, which were used for lighting in the 19th century.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] Ernst Lecher in 1888 showed that the current through an electric arc could be oscillatory.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] An oscillator was built by Elihu Thomson in 1892 by placing an LC tuned circuit in parallel with an electric arc and included a magnetic blowout.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] The arc oscillator was rediscovered and popularized by William Duddell in 1900.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] Duddell, a student at London Technical College, was investigating the hissing arc effect.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] He attached an LC circuit (tuned circuit) to the electrodes of an arc lamp, and the negative resistance of the arc excited oscillation in the tuned circuit.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] Some of the energy was radiated as sound waves by the arc, producing a musical tone.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] Duddell demonstrated his oscillator before the London Institute of Electrical Engineers by sequentially connecting different tuned circuits across the arc to play the national anthem "God Save the Queen".
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] Duddell's "singing arc" did not generate frequencies above the audio range.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] In 1902 Danish physicists Valdemar Poulsen and P.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] Pederson were able to increase the frequency produced into the radio range by operating the arc in a hydrogen atmosphere with a magnetic field, inventing the Poulsen arc radio transmitter, the first continuous wave radio transmitter, which was used through the 1920s.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] The vacuum-tube feedback oscillator was invented around 1912, when it was discovered that feedback ("regeneration") in the recently invented audion (triode) vacuum tube could produce oscillations.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] At least six researchers independently made this discovery, although not all of them can be said to have a role in the invention of the oscillator.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] In the summer of 1912, Edwin Armstrong observed oscillations in audion radio receiver circuits and went on to use positive feedback in his invention of the regenerative receiver.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] Austrian Alexander Meissner independently discovered positive feedback and invented oscillators in March 1913.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] Irving Langmuir at General Electric observed feedback in 1913.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] Fritz Lowenstein may have preceded the others with a crude oscillator in late 1911.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] Round patented amplifying and oscillating circuits in 1913.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] In August 1912, Lee De Forest, the inventor of the audion, had also observed oscillations in his amplifiers, but he didn't understand the significance and tried to eliminate it until he read Armstrong's patents in 1914, which he promptly challenged.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] Armstrong and De Forest fought a protracted legal battle over the rights to the "regenerative" oscillator circuit which has been called "the most complicated patent litigation in the history of radio".
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] De Forest ultimately won before the Supreme Court in 1934 on technical grounds, but most sources regard Armstrong's claim as the stronger one.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] The first and most widely used relaxation oscillator circuit, the astable multivibrator, was invented in 1917 by French engineers Henri Abraham and Eugene Bloch.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] They called their cross-coupled, dual-vacuum-tube circuit a *multivibrateur*, because the square-wave signal it produced was rich in harmonics, compared to the sinusoidal signal of other vacuum-tube oscillators.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] Vacuum-tube feedback oscillators became the basis of radio transmission by 1920.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] However, the triode vacuum tube oscillator performed poorly above 300 MHz because of interelectrode capacitance.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] To reach higher frequencies, new "transit time" (velocity modulation) vacuum tubes were developed, in which electrons traveled in "bunches" through the tube.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] The first of these was the Barkhausen–Kurz oscillator (1920), the first tube to produce power in the UHF range.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] The most important and widely used were the klystron (R. and S.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] Varian, 1937) and the cavity magnetron (J.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] Mathematical conditions for feedback oscillations, now called the Barkhausen criterion, were derived by Heinrich Georg Barkhausen in 1921.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] He also showed that all linear oscillators must have negative resistance.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] The first analysis of a nonlinear electronic oscillator model, the Van der Pol oscillator, was done by Balthasar van der Pol in 1927.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] He originated the term "relaxation oscillation" and was first to distinguish between linear and relaxation oscillators.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] He showed that the stability of the oscillations (limit cycles) in actual oscillators was due to the nonlinearity of the amplifying device.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] Further advances in mathematical analysis of oscillation were made by Hendrik Wade Bode and Harry Nyquist in the 1930s.
[src:audio-synthesis/oscillator-electronics] In 1969 Kaneyuki Kurokawa derived necessary and sufficient conditions for oscillation in negative-resistance circuits, which form the basis of modern microwave oscillator design.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] A **synthesizer** (also **synthesiser** or **synth**) is an electronic musical instrument that generates audio signals.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Synthesizers typically create sounds by generating waveforms through methods including subtractive synthesis, additive synthesis, and frequency modulation synthesis.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] These sounds may be altered by components such as filters, which cut or boost frequencies; envelopes, which control articulation, or how notes begin and end; and low-frequency oscillators, which modulate parameters such as pitch, volume, or filter characteristics affecting timbre.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Synthesizers are typically played with keyboards or controlled by sequencers, software or other instruments, and can be synchronized to other equipment via MIDI.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Synthesizer-like instruments emerged in the United States in the mid-20th century with instruments such as the RCA Mark II, which was controlled with punch cards and used hundreds of vacuum tubes.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The Moog synthesizer, developed by Robert Moog and first sold in 1964, is credited for pioneering concepts such as voltage-controlled oscillators, envelopes, noise generators, filters, and sequencers.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In 1970, the smaller, cheaper Minimoog standardized synthesizers as self-contained instruments with built-in keyboards, unlike the larger modular synthesizers before it.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In 1978, Sequential Circuits released the Prophet-5, which used microprocessors to allow users to store sounds for the first time.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] MIDI, a standardized means of synchronizing electronic instruments, was introduced in 1982 and remains an industry standard.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The Yamaha DX7, launched in 1983, was a major success and popularized digital synthesis.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Software synthesizers now can be run as plug-ins or embedded on microchips.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In the 21st century, analog synthesizers returned to popularity with the advent of cheaper manufacturing.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Synthesizers were initially viewed as avant-garde, valued by the 1960s psychedelic and countercultural scenes but with little perceived commercial potential.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] *Switched-On Bach* (1968)*,* a bestselling album of Bach compositions arranged for synthesizer by Wendy Carlos, took synthesizers to the mainstream.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] They were adopted by electronic acts and pop and rock groups in the 1960s and 1970s and were widely used in 1980s music.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Sampling, introduced with the Fairlight synthesizer in 1979, has influenced genres such as electronic and hip hop music.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Today, the synthesizer is used in nearly every genre and is considered one of the most important instruments in the music industry.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] As electricity became more widely available, the early 20th century saw the invention of electronic musical instruments including the Telharmonium, Trautonium, ondes Martenot and theremin.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In the late 1930s, the Hammond Organ Company built the Novachord, a large instrument powered by 72 voltage-controlled amplifiers and 146 vacuum tubes.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In 1948, the Canadian engineer Hugh Le Caine completed the electronic sackbut, a precursor to voltage-controlled synthesizers, with keyboard sensitivity allowing for vibrato, glissando, and attack control.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In 1957, Harry Olson and Herbert Belar completed the RCA Mark II Sound Synthesizer at the RCA laboratories in Princeton, New Jersey.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The instrument read punched paper tape that controlled an analog synthesizer containing 750 vacuum tubes.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] It was acquired by the Columbia-Princeton Electronic Music Center and used almost exclusively by Milton Babbitt, a composer at Princeton University.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The authors of *Analog Days* define "the early years of the synthesizer" as between 1964 and the mid-1970s, beginning with the debut of the Moog synthesizer, designed by the American engineer Robert Moog.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The Moog was composed of separate modules connected by patch cables that generate, shape or control sound.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Moog developed a means of controlling pitch through voltage, the voltage-controlled oscillator.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] This, along with Moog components such as envelopes, noise generators, filters, and sequencers, became standard components in synthesizers.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Around the same period, the American engineer Don Buchla created the Buchla Modular Electronic Music System.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Instead of a conventional keyboard, Buchla's system used touchplates which transmitted control voltages depending on finger position and force.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] However, the Moog's keyboard made it more accessible and marketable to musicians, and keyboards became the standard means of controlling synthesizers.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Moog and Buchla initially avoided the word *synthesizer* for their instruments, as it was associated with the RCA synthesizer; however, by the 1970s, it had become the standard term.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In 1970, Moog launched a cheaper, smaller synthesizer, the Minimoog.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] It was the first synthesizer sold in music stores, and was more practical for live performance.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] It standardized the concept of synthesizers as self-contained instruments with built-in keyboards.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In the early 1970s, the British composer Ken Freeman introduced the first string synthesizer, designed to emulate string sections.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] After retail stores started selling synthesizers in 1971, other synthesizer companies were established, including ARP in the US and EMS in the UK.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] ARP's products included the ARP 2600, which folded into a carrying case and had built-in speakers, and the Odyssey, a rival to the Minimoog.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The less expensive EMS synthesizers were used by European art rock and progressive rock acts including Brian Eno and Pink Floyd.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Designs for synthesizers appeared in the amateur electronics market, such as a design published in *Practical Electronics* in 1973.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] By the mid-1970s, ARP was the world's largest synthesizer manufacturer, though it closed in 1981.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Early synthesizers were monophonic, meaning they could only play one note at a time.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Some of the earliest commercial polyphonic synthesizers were created by the American engineer Tom Oberheim, such as the OB-X (1979).
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In 1978, the American company Sequential Circuits released the Prophet-5, the first fully programmable polyphonic synthesizer.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Whereas previous synthesizers required users to adjust cables and knobs to change sounds, with no guarantee of exactly recreating a sound, the Prophet-5 used microprocessors to store sounds in patch memory.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] This facilitated a move from synthesizers creating unpredictable sounds to producing "a standard package of familiar sounds".
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The synthesizer market grew dramatically in the 1980s.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] 1982 saw the introduction of MIDI, a standardized means of synchronizing electronic instruments; it remains an industry standard.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] An influential sampling synthesizer, the Fairlight CMI, was released in 1979, with the ability to record and play back samples at different pitches.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Though its high price made it inaccessible to amateurs, it was adopted by high-profile pop musicians including Kate Bush and Peter Gabriel.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The success of the Fairlight drove competition, improving sampling technology and lowering prices.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Early competing samplers included the E-mu Emulator in 1981 and the Akai S-series in 1985.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In 1983, Yamaha released the first commercially successful digital synthesizer, the Yamaha DX7.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Based on frequency modulation (FM) synthesis developed by the Stanford University engineer John Chowning, the DX7 was characterized by its *harsh*, *glassy* and *chilly* sounds, compared to the *warm* and *fuzzy* sounds of analog synthesis.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The DX7 was the first synthesizer to sell more than 100,000 unitsand remains one of the bestselling in history.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Digital synthesizers typically contained preset sounds emulating acoustic instruments, with algorithms controlled with menus and buttons.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The Synclavier, made with FM technology licensed from Yamaha, offered features such as 16-bit sampling and digital recording.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] With a starting price of $13,000, its use was limited to universities, studios and wealthy artists.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The Roland D-50 (1987) blended Roland's linear arithmetic algorithm with samples, and was the first mass-produced synthesizer with built-in digital effects such as delay, reverb and chorus.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In 1988, the Japanese manufacturer Korg released the M1, a digital synthesizer workstation featuring sampled transients and loops.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] With more than 250,000 units sold, it remains the bestselling synthesizer in history.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The advent of digital synthesizers led to a downturn in interest in analog synthesizers in the following decade.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] ReBirth by Propellerhead Software and Reality by Seer Systems, the first software synthesizers that could be played in real time via MIDI, were released in 1997.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In 1999, an update to the music software Cubase allowed users to run software instruments (including synthesizers) as plug-ins, triggering a wave of new software instruments.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Propellerhead's Reason, released in 2000, introduced an array of recognizable virtual studio equipment.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The market for patchable and modular synthesizers rebounded in the late 1990s.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In the 2000s, older analog synthesizers regained popularity, sometimes selling for much more than their original prices.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In the 2010s, new, affordable analog synthesizers were introduced by companies including Moog, Korg, Arturia and Dave Smith Instruments.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The renewed interest is credited to the appeal of imperfect *organic* sounds and simpler interfaces, and modern surface-mount technology making analog synthesizers cheaper and faster to manufacture.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Early synthesizers were viewed as avant-garde, valued by the 1960s psychedelic and counter-cultural scenes for their ability to make new sounds, but with little perceived commercial potential.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] *Switched-On Bach* (1968), a bestselling album of Bach compositions arranged for Moog synthesizer by Wendy Carlos, demonstrated that synthesizers could be more than "random noise machines", taking them to the mainstream.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] However, debates were held about the appropriateness of synthesizers in baroque music, and according to the *Guardian* they were quickly abandoned in "serious classical circles".
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Today, the synthesizer is one of the most important instruments in the music industry, used in nearly every genre.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] It is considered by the authors of *Analog Days* as "the only innovation that can stand alongside the electric guitar as a great new instrument of the age of electricity ...
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The Moog was adopted by 1960s rock acts including the Doors, the Grateful Dead, the Rolling Stones, the Beatles, and Keith Emerson.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Emerson was the first major rock musician to perform with the Moog and it became a trademark of his performances, helping take his band Emerson, Lake & Palmer to global stardom.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] According to *Analog Days*, the likes of Emerson, with his Moog performances, "did for the keyboard what Jimi Hendrix did for the guitar".
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] String synthesizers were used by 1970s progressive rock bands including Camel, Caravan, Electric Light Orchestra, Gentle Giant and Renaissance.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The portable Minimoog (1970), much smaller than the modular synthesizers before it, made synthesizers more common in live performance.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Early synthesizers could only play one note at a time, making them suitable for basslines, leads and solos.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] With the rise of polyphonic synthesizers in the 1970s and 1980s, "the keyboard in rock once more started to revert to the background, to be used for fills and atmosphere rather than for soloing".
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Queen included statements in their 1970s album notes specifying that no synthesisers had been used, but added them in their 1980 album *The Game*.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The Minimoog took a place in mainstream African-American music, most notably in the work of Stevie Wonder, and in jazz, such as the work of Sun Ra.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In the late 1970s and the early 1980s, the Minimoog was widely used in the emerging disco genre by artists including Abba and Giorgio Moroder.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Sampling, introduced with the Fairlight synthesizer in 1979, has influenced all genres of music and had a major influence on the development of electronic and hip hop music.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In the 1970s, electronic music composers such as Jean Michel Jarre and Isao Tomita released successful synthesizer-led instrumental albums.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] This influenced the emergence of synth-pop from the late 1970s to the early 1980s.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The sequencer-based Roland TB-303 (1981), in conjunction with the Roland TR-808 and TR-909 drum machines, became a foundation of electronic dance music genres such as house and techno when producers acquired cheap second-hand units later in the decade.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The authors of *Analog Days* connect the synthesizer's origins in 1960s psychedelia to the raves and British Second Summer of Love of the 1980s and the club scenes of the 1990s and 2000s.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Gary Numan's 1979 hits "Are 'Friends' Electric?" and "Cars" made heavy use of synthesizers.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] OMD's "Enola Gay" (1980) used distinctive electronic percussion and a synthesized melody.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Soft Cell used a synthesized melody on their 1981 hit "Tainted Love".
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Nick Rhodes, the keyboardist of Duran Duran, used synthesizers including the Roland Jupiter-4 and Jupiter-8.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Chart hits include Depeche Mode's "Just Can't Get Enough" (1981), the Human League's "Don't You Want Me" and works by Ultravox.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In the 1980s, digital synthesizers were widely used in pop music.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The Yamaha DX7, released in 1983, became a pop staple, used on songs by A-ha, Kenny Loggins, Kool & the Gang.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Its E PIANO 1 preset became particularly famous, especially for power ballads, and was used by artists including Whitney Houston, Chicago, Prince, Phil Collins, Luther Vandross, Billy Ocean, and Celine Dion.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Korg M1 presets were widely used in 1990s house music, beginning with Madonna's 1990 single "Vogue".
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Synthesizers are common in film and television soundtracks.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In 1969, Mort Garson used a Moog to compose a soundtrack for the televised footage of the Apollo 11 moonwalk, creating a link between electronic music and space in the American popular imagination.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] ARP synthesizers were used to create sound effects for the 1977 science fiction films *Close Encounters of the Third Kind* and *Star Wars*, including the voice of the robot R2-D2.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In the 1970s and 1980s, synthesizers were used in the scores for thrillers and horror films including *A Clockwork Orange* (1971), *Apocalypse Now* (1979), *The Fog* (1980) and *Manhunter* (1986).
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Brad Fiedel used a Prophet synthesizer to record the soundtrack for *The Terminator* (1984), and the filmmaker John Carpenter used them extensively for his soundtracks.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Synthesizers were used to create themes for television shows including *Knight Rider* (1982)*, Twin Peaks* (1990) and *Stranger Things* (2016).
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The rise of the synthesizer led to major changes in the music industry, including job displacement, comparable to the 1920s arrival of sound in film, which put live musicians accompanying silent films out of work.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] With its ability to imitate instruments such as strings and horns, the synthesizer threatened the jobs of session musicians by allowing one keyboardist or music programmer to produce the same range of sounds as an entire orchestra.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] For a period, the Moog was banned from use in union work, a restriction negotiated by the American Federation of Musicians (AFM).
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The musician Walter Sear persuaded the AFM that the synthesizer demanded skill, and the category of *synthesizer player* was accepted into the union.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] However, players were subject to "suspicion and hostility" for years.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In 1982, following a tour by Barry Manilow using synthesizers instead of an orchestra, the British Musicians' Union attempted to ban synthesizers, attracting controversy.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In the 1980s, a few musicians skilled at programming the Yamaha DX7 found employment creating sounds for other acts.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Synthesizers generate audio through various forms of analog and digital synthesis.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Oscillators produce waveforms (such as sawtooth, sine, or pulse waves) with different timbres.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Voltage-controlled amplifiers (VCAs) control the volume or gain of the audio signal.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] VCAs can be modulated by other components, such as LFOs and envelopes.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] A VCA is a preamp that boosts (amplifies) the electronic signal before passing it on to an external or built-in power amplifier, as well as a means to control its amplitude (volume) using an attenuator.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The gain of the VCA is affected by a *control voltage* (CV), coming from an envelope generator, an LFO, the keyboard or some other source.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Envelopes control how sounds change over time.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] They may control parameters such as amplitude (volume), filters (frequencies), or pitch.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Low-frequency oscillators (LFOs) produce waveforms used to modulate parameters, such as the pitch of oscillators (producing vibrato).
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Filters remove frequencies from the audio signal, similarly to equalization, to shape sounds.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] They typically include controls to set the point at which frequencies are attenuated, and to add resonance.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Common types include low-pass filters, which remove audio above a specified frequency, and high-pass filters, which do the opposite.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Filters may be controlled with envelopes or LFOs.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Arpeggiators take input chords and convert them into arpeggios.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] They usually include controls for speed, range and mode (the movement of the arpeggio).
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Synthesizers are often controlled with electronic or digital keyboards or MIDI controller keyboards, which may be built into the synthesizer unit or attached via connections such as CV/gate, USB, or MIDI.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Keyboards may offer expression such as velocity sensitivity and aftertouch, allowing for more control over the sound.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Synthesizer clones are unlicensed recreations of previous synthesizers, often marketed as affordable versions of famous musical equipment.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Clones are available as physical instruments and software.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Companies that have sold software clones include Arturia and Native Instruments.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Behringer manufactures equipment modelled on instruments including the Minimoog, Pro-One, and TB-303, and drum machines such as the TR-808.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Other synthesizer clones include the MiniMOD (a series of Eurorack modules based on the Minimoog), the Intellijel Atlantis (based on the SH-101), and the x0x Heart (based on the TB-303).
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Creating clones of older hardware is legal where the patents have expired.
[src:audio-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In 1997, Mackie lost their lawsuit against Behringer as copyright law in the United States did not cover their circuit board designs.
[src:audio-synthesis/subtractive-synthesis] Subtractive synthesis relies on source sounds that have overtones, such as non-sinusoidal waveforms like square and triangle waves, or white and pink noise.
[src:audio-synthesis/subtractive-synthesis] These overtones are then modulated to alter the source sound.
[src:audio-synthesis/subtractive-synthesis] This modulation can happen in a wide variety of ways, such as voltage-controlled or low-pass filters.
[src:audio-synthesis/subtractive-synthesis] The technology developed in experimental electronic studios which were primarily focused on telecommunications and military applications.
[src:audio-synthesis/subtractive-synthesis] Early examples include Bell Labs' Voder (1937–8).
[src:audio-synthesis/subtractive-synthesis] Composers began applying the concept of subtractive synthesis beyond the recording studio in concert music.
[src:audio-synthesis/subtractive-synthesis] Henri Pousseur's *Scambi* (1957) subjects white noise to filters and uses the resulting sounds to create montages.
[src:audio-synthesis/subtractive-synthesis] *Mikrophonie I* (1964) by Karlheinz Stockhausen uses a tam-tam and a microphone as the primary sound source which is then filtered extensively by two sound projectionists.
[src:audio-synthesis/subtractive-synthesis] Until the advent of digital synthesizers, subtractive synthesis was the nearly universal electronic method of sound production.
[src:audio-synthesis/subtractive-synthesis] Its popularity was due largely to its relative simplicity.
[src:audio-synthesis/subtractive-synthesis] Subtractive synthesis was so prevalent in analog synthesizers that it is sometimes called "analog synthesis".
[src:audio-synthesis/subtractive-synthesis] Programmable sound generators (PSG) relied heavily on subtractive synthesis.
[src:audio-synthesis/subtractive-synthesis] PSGs were used in many personal computers, arcade games, and home consoles such as the Commodore 64, Atari ST, Mattel's Intellivision, Sega's Master System, and the ZX Spectrum.
[src:audio-synthesis/subtractive-synthesis] Subtractive synthesis has become a catchall for a method where source sounds are modulated, and it is sometimes applied inappropriately.
[src:audio-synthesis/subtractive-synthesis] The following is an example of subtractive synthesis as it might occur in an electronic instrument to emulate the sound of a plucked string.
[src:audio-synthesis/subtractive-synthesis] It was created with a personal computer program designed to emulate an analogue subtractive synthesizer.
[src:audio-synthesis/subtractive-synthesis] First, an electronic oscillator produces a relatively complex waveform with audible overtones.
[src:audio-synthesis/subtractive-synthesis] Only one oscillator is necessary, and the number can vary widely.
[src:audio-synthesis/subtractive-synthesis] The pulse-width modulated sounds are now combined at equal volume.
[src:audio-synthesis/subtractive-synthesis] Combining them at different volumes would create different timbres.
[src:audio-synthesis/subtractive-synthesis] The result is a 2-second **source sound**, which is ready for subtractive synthesis.
[src:audio-synthesis/subtractive-synthesis] The combined wave is passed through a voltage-controlled amplifier connected to an envelope generator.
[src:audio-synthesis/subtractive-synthesis] The parameters of the sound's envelope (attack, decay, sustain and release) are manipulated to change its sound.
[src:audio-synthesis/subtractive-synthesis] In this case, the decay is vastly increased, sustain is reduced, and the release shortened.
[src:audio-synthesis/subtractive-synthesis] To better emulate the sound of a plucked string, the filter's cutoff frequency is raised.
[src:audio-synthesis/wavetable-synthesis] To produce output, the system selects a starting point within the table and a length, and the system loops through that section of the stored waveforms and plays it repeatedly.
[src:audio-synthesis/wavetable-synthesis] Each amplitude value is read from memory in turn, often stored in ROM.
[src:audio-synthesis/wavetable-synthesis] The series of numbers being read is sent into an digital-to-analog converter, which converts the value into an electrical signal to produce an audible signal.
[src:audio-synthesis/wavetable-synthesis] Most systems include the capability to mix multiple samples together to produce more complex output.
[src:audio-synthesis/wavetable-synthesis] One example of the technique is in the Waldorf Microwave synthesizer which had loadable wavetables.
[src:audio-synthesis/wavetable-synthesis] One consisted of the statement "nineteen twenty" from a voice synthesizer.
[src:audio-synthesis/wavetable-synthesis] By selecting different starting points and lengths within this sample, a wide variety of sounds can be produced.
[src:audio-synthesis/wavetable-synthesis] Wavetable synthesis was invented by Max Mathews in 1958 as part of MUSIC II.
[src:audio-synthesis/wavetable-synthesis] Hal Chamberlin discussed wavetable synthesis in Byte's September 1977 issue.
[src:audio-synthesis/wavetable-synthesis] Wolfgang Palm of Palm Products GmbH (PPG) developed his version in the late 1970s and published it in 1979.
[src:audio-synthesis/wavetable-synthesis] The technique has since been used as the primary synthesis method in synthesizers built by PPG and Waldorf Music and as an auxiliary synthesis method by Ensoniq and Access.
[src:audio-synthesis/wavetable-synthesis] It is currently used in hardware synthesizers from Waldorf Music and in software synthesizers for PCs and tablets, including apps offered by PPG and Waldorf, among others.
[src:audio-synthesis/wavetable-synthesis] It was also independently developed by Michael McNabb, who used it in his 1978 composition *Dreamsong*.
[src:audio-synthesis/wavetable-synthesis] Electronic synthesizers using digital techniques generally produce sounds by producing a digital value, a number, and then sending that value to an digital-to-analog converter (DAC) that produces a scaled output voltage.
[src:audio-synthesis/wavetable-synthesis] For instance, to produce a triangle wave or sawtooth, systems used a register containing a starting value, normally zero, and then periodically increase or decrease the value using an adder or phase accumulator.
[src:audio-synthesis/wavetable-synthesis] The value in the register is continually sent to the DAC to produce output.
[src:audio-synthesis/wavetable-synthesis] The pitch of the resulting sound can be changed by how rapidly the adder is called.
[src:audio-synthesis/wavetable-synthesis] Wavetable synthesis is a relatively simple modification of this sort of system.
[src:audio-synthesis/wavetable-synthesis] Instead of the value at any particular instantly being periodically modified by a simple function like addition, the specific value for any instant is read from memory containing a series of values making up multiple arbitrary, single-cycle waveforms.
[src:audio-synthesis/wavetable-synthesis] This allows the waveform to have any shape, not just simple ones like triangles or sines.
[src:audio-synthesis/wavetable-synthesis] With that exception, the system is otherwise the same; values are read into the register at a rate that produces the desired pitch, and the output of the register is used to feed a DAC that produces the output signal.
[src:audio-synthesis/wavetable-synthesis] In order to produce a different sound, all that has to be changed is a single value pointing to the starting point of the waveform in memory.
[src:audio-synthesis/wavetable-synthesis] Because the table contains many different waveforms, playing a longer sample that includes several different waveforms may result in odd side-effects when the system crosses the boundaries between the individual waveforms.
[src:audio-synthesis/wavetable-synthesis] Digital interpolation between adjacent waveforms allows for dynamic and smooth changes of the timbre of the tone produced.
[src:audio-synthesis/wavetable-synthesis] Additional effects can be provided by reading the waveform forward or backward, and further controlled in a number of ways, for example, by use of an LFO, envelope, pressure or velocity.
[src:audio-synthesis/wavetable-synthesis] Many wavetables used in PPG and Ensoniq synthesizers can simulate the methods used by analog synthesizers, such as pulse-width modulation by utilising a number of square waves of different duty cycles.
[src:audio-synthesis/wavetable-synthesis] In this way, when the wavetable is swept, the duty cycle of the pulse wave will appear to change over time.
[src:audio-synthesis/wavetable-synthesis] As the early Ensoniq wavetable synthesizers had non resonant filters (the PPG Wave synthesizers used Curtis analogue resonant filters), some wavetables contained highly resonant waveforms to overcome this limitation of the filters.
[src:audio-synthesis/wavetable-synthesis] In 1992, with the introduction of the Creative Labs Sound Blaster 16 the term "wavetable" started to be (incorrectly) applied as a marketing term to their sound card.
[src:audio-synthesis/wavetable-synthesis] However, these sound cards did not employ any form of wavetable synthesis, but rather PCM samples and FM synthesis.
[src:audio-synthesis/wavetable-synthesis] The creation of new wavetables was previously a difficult process unless supported by specialized editing facilities and (near) real-time playback of edited wavetables on the synthesizer.
[src:audio-synthesis/wavetable-synthesis] Such editors often required the use of extra hardware devices like the PPG Waveterm or were only present in expensive models like the Waldorf WAVE.
[src:audio-synthesis/wavetable-synthesis] More commonly, pre-computed wavetables could be added via memory cards or sent to the synthesizer via MIDI.
[src:audio-synthesis/wavetable-synthesis] Today, wavetables can be created more easily by software and auditioned directly on a computer.
[src:audio-synthesis/wavetable-synthesis] Since all waveforms used in wavetable synthesis are periodic, the time-domain and frequency-domain representation are exact equivalents of each other and both can be used simultaneously to define waveforms and wavetables.
[src:audio-synthesis/wavetable-synthesis] During playback, the sound produced can be harmonically changed by moving to another point in the wavetable, usually under the control of an envelope generator or low-frequency oscillator but frequently by any number of modulators (matrix modulation).
[src:audio-synthesis/wavetable-synthesis] Doing this modifies the harmonic content of the output wave in real time, producing sounds that can imitate acoustic instruments or be totally abstract, which is where this method of sound creation excels.
[src:audio-synthesis/wavetable-synthesis] The technique is especially useful for evolving synth pads, where the sound changes slowly over time.
[src:audio-synthesis/wavetable-synthesis] It is often necessary to 'audition' each position in a wavetable and to scan through it, forwards and backwards, in order to make good use of it, though selecting random wavetables, start positions, end positions and directions of scan can also produce satisfying musical results.
[src:audio-synthesis/wavetable-synthesis] It is worth noting that most wavetable synthesizers also employ other synthesis methods to further shape the output waveform, such as subtractive synthesis (filters), phase modulation, frequency modulation and AM (ring) modulation.
[src:audio-synthesis/wavetable-synthesis] , where the data at addresses from 63 to 67 are zoomed.
[src:audio-synthesis/wavetable-synthesis] On Csound, it is called *f-table* (function table), and used for various purposes including: wavetable-lookup synthesis, waveshaping, MIDI note mapping, and storing ordered pitch-class sets.
[src:audio-synthesis/wavetable-synthesis] However, the derived term "*wavetable synthesis*" seems slightly confused by the later developments of derived algorithm.
[src:audio-synthesis/wavetable-synthesis] In the mid-2000s, confusion in terminology cropped up yet-again.
[src:audio-synthesis/wavetable-synthesis] A subclass of generic wavetable synthesis, *i.e.* McNabb and Palm's multiple wavetable synthesis, tends to be erroneously referred as if it was a generic class of whole wavetable synthesis family, exclusively.
[src:audio-synthesis/wavetable-synthesis] As a result, the difficulty of maintaining consistency between concepts and terminology during rapid technological development is noteworthy.
[src:audio-synthesis/wavetable-synthesis] For this reason the term "Table-lookup synthesis" is explained at length in this article.
